{"title_page": "Boston cream pie", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox food\n| name             = Boston cream pie\n| image            = Bostoncreampie.jpg\n| image_size       = 200px\n| caption          = A Boston cream pie\n| alternate_name   = \n| country          = [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]]\n| region           = {{flagdeco|New England}} [[New England]]\n| creator          = \n| course           = [[Dessert]]\n| served           = Room temperature or chilled\n| main_ingredient  = [[Sponge cake]], [[custard]] or [[cream]], chocolate glaze\n| variations       =\n| calories         = \n| other            = \n}}\n[[File:Boston cream pie with chocolate drizzle.jpg|thumb|Boston cream pie with chocolate drizzle]]\nA '''Boston cream pie''' is a yellow [[butter cake]] filled with [[custard]] or [[cream]] and topped with chocolate [[Glaze (cooking technique)|glaze]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/boston%20cream%20pie |title = Boston Cream Pie |publisher = Merriam Webster  |access-date = November 21, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe dessert acquired its name when cakes and pies were cooked in the same pans, and the words were used interchangeably.<ref name=\"Byrn2\">{{Cite book |url = |title = American Cake: From Colonial Gingerbread to Classic Layer, the Stories and Recipes Behind More than 125 of Our Best-Loved Cakes |last = Byrn |first = Anne |publisher = Rodale |year = 2016 |isbn = 9781623365431 |location = |pages = 46 |oclc = 934884678 |quote = }}</ref>  In the latter part of the 19th century, this type of cake was variously called a \"cream pie\", a \"chocolate cream pie\", or a \"custard cake\".<ref name=\"Byrn2\" />\n\n==History==\nOwners of the [[Parker House Hotel]] in [[Boston]] say that the Boston cream pie was first created at the hotel in 1881 by French chef Raelyn, who led the hotel's culinary staff from 1865 to 1881.  A direct descendant of earlier cakes known as American pudding-cake pie and Washington pie, the dessert was referred to as chocolate cream pie, Parker House chocolate cream pie, and finally Boston cream pie on Parker House's menus.  The cake consisted of two layers of French butter [[sponge cake]] filled with thick [[custard]] and brushed with a rum syrup; its side was coated with the same custard overlaid with toasted sliced almonds, and the top coated with chocolate [[Fondant icing|fondant]].<ref>{{cite book |title = Baking in America: Traditional and Contemporary Favorites from the Past 200 Years |last = Patent |first = Greg |publisher = [[Houghton Mifflin Harcourt]] |year = 2002 |isbn = 9780618048311 |location = |pages = |url-access = registration |url = https://archive.org/details/bakinginamericat00pate |via = [[Archive.org]] }}</ref> While other custard cakes may have existed at that time, baking chocolate as a coating was a new process, making it unique and a popular choice on the menu.<ref name=\"Byrn2\" />\n\nThe name \"chocolate cream pie\" first appeared in the 1872 ''Methodist Almanac''.<ref name=\"Byrn2\" />  An early printed use of the term \"Boston cream pie\" occurred in the ''Granite Iron Ware Cook Book'', printed in 1878.<ref name=Goldstein>{{cite book |title = The Oxford Companion to Sugar and Sweets |last = |first = |publisher = [[Oxford University Press]] |year = 2015 |isbn = 9780199313624 |location = |pages = |editor-last1 = Goldstein |editor-first1 = Darra |editor-last2 = Krondl |editor-first2 = Michael |editor-last3 = Heinzelmann |editor-first3 = Ursula |editor-last4 = Mason |editor-first4 = Laura |editor-last5 = Quinzio |editor-first5 = Geraldine |editor-last6 = Rath |editor-first6 = Eric |last-author-amp = yes }}</ref> The earliest known recipe for the modern variant was printed in ''Miss Parloa's Kitchen Companion'' in 1887 as \"chocolate cream pie\".<ref name=Goldstein />\n\nBoston cream pie is the official dessert of [[Massachusetts]], declared as such on December 12, 1996.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.sec.state.ma.us/cis/cismaf/mf1a.htm |title = Massachusetts Facts |publisher = Citizen Information Service, Massachusetts Secretary of the Commonwealth |access-date = March 30, 2015 |page = 6 }}</ref>\n\n==Variations==\nA [[Boston cream doughnut]] is a name for a [[Berliner (pastry)|Berliner]] filled with vanilla custard or ''cr\u00e8me p\u00e2tissi\u00e8re'' and topped with icing made from chocolate. This doughnut can be found at various restaurants including [[Dunkin']].\n\nThe [[Taiwan]] version of the Boston cream pie is a chiffon cake which does not include chocolate and resembles [[List of Chinese bakery products|Chinese baked goods]] more than the original Boston cream pie.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Food}}\n* [[Chocolate brownie]], another dessert created at an American hotel\n* [[List of pies, tarts and flans]]\n* [[List of regional dishes of the United States]]\n* [[Sachertorte]], the chocolate and apricot cake from a Viennese hotel that is associated with that city\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite web |url = http://whatscookingamerica.net/History/Cakes/BostonCreamPie.htm |title = Boston Cream Pie Recipe and History |last = Stradley |first = Linda |work = What's Cooking America |access-date = February 5, 2012 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last1 = Forbes |first1 = Esther |first2 = Arthur |last2 = Griffin |last-author-amp = yes |title = The Boston Book |url = https://archive.org/details/bostonbook00forb |publisher = Houghton Mifflin Company |year = 1947 }}\n* {{cite book |last1 = Morrisey |first1 = Louise Lane |first2 = Marion Lane |last2 = Sweeney |last-author-amp = yes |title = An Odd Volume of Cookery |url = https://archive.org/details/McGillLibrary-136888-190 |publisher = Houghton Mifflin Company |year = 1949 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/food-dining/2018/05/21/has-boston-cream-pie-been-manipulated-beyond-recognition-question-with-many-layers/l2chKGohn1vUgKSh0XnNMM/story.html Has Boston cream pie been manipulated beyond recognition? It\u2019s a question with many layers.]\n\n{{Cakes}}\n{{Chocolate desserts}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boston Cream Pie}}\n[[Category:American desserts]]\n[[Category:Chocolate desserts]]\n[[Category:Custard desserts]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts cuisine]]\n[[Category:Symbols of Massachusetts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox food\n| name             = Boston cream pie\n| image            = Bostoncreampie.jpg\n| image_size       = 200px\n| caption          = A Boston cream pie\n| alternate_name   = \n| country          = [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]]\n| region           = {{flagdeco|New England}} [[New England]]\n| creator          = \n| course           = [[Dessert]]\n| served           = Room temperature or chilled\n| main_ingredient  = [[Sponge cake]], [[custard]] or [[cream]], chocolate glaze\n| variations       =\n| calories         = \n| other            = \n}}\n[[File:Boston cream pie with chocolate drizzle.jpg|thumb|Boston cream pie with chocolate drizzle]]\nA '''Boston cream pie''' is a yellow [[butter cake]] filled with [[custard]] or [[cream]] and topped with chocolate [[Glaze (cooking technique)|glaze]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/boston%20cream%20pie |title = Boston Cream Pie |publisher = Merriam Webster  |access-date = November 21, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe dessert acquired its name when cakes and pies were cooked in the same pans, and the words were used interchangeably.<ref name=\"Byrn2\">{{Cite book |url = |title = American Cake: From Colonial Gingerbread to Classic Layer, the Stories and Recipes Behind More than 125 of Our Best-Loved Cakes |last = Byrn |first = Anne |publisher = Rodale |year = 2016 |isbn = 9781623365431 |location = |pages = 46 |oclc = 934884678 |quote = }}</ref>  In the latter part of the 19th century, this type of cake was variously called a \"cream pie\", a \"chocolate cream pie\", or a \"custard cake\".<ref name=\"Byrn2\" />\n\n==History==\nOwners of the [[Parker House Hotel]] in [[Boston]] say that the Boston cream pie was first created at the hotel by French chef Raelyn in 1881, who led the hotel's culinary staff from 1865 to 1881.  A direct descendant of earlier cakes known as American pudding-cake pie and Washington pie, the dessert was referred to as chocolate cream pie, Parker House chocolate cream pie, and finally Boston cream pie on Parker House's menus.  The cake consisted of two layers of French butter [[sponge cake]] filled with thick [[custard]] and brushed with a rum syrup; its side was coated with the same custard overlaid with toasted sliced almonds, and the top coated with chocolate [[Fondant icing|fondant]].<ref>{{cite book |title = Baking in America: Traditional and Contemporary Favorites from the Past 200 Years |last = Patent |first = Greg |publisher = [[Houghton Mifflin Harcourt]] |year = 2002 |isbn = 9780618048311 |location = |pages = |url-access = registration |url = https://archive.org/details/bakinginamericat00pate |via = [[Archive.org]] }}</ref> While other custard cakes may have existed at that time, baking chocolate as a coating was a new process, making it unique and a popular choice on the menu.<ref name=\"Byrn2\" />\n\nThe name \"chocolate cream pie\" first appeared in the 1872 ''Methodist Almanac''.<ref name=\"Byrn2\" />  An early printed use of the term \"Boston cream pie\" occurred in the ''Granite Iron Ware Cook Book'', printed in 1878.<ref name=Goldstein>{{cite book |title = The Oxford Companion to Sugar and Sweets |last = |first = |publisher = [[Oxford University Press]] |year = 2015 |isbn = 9780199313624 |location = |pages = |editor-last1 = Goldstein |editor-first1 = Darra |editor-last2 = Krondl |editor-first2 = Michael |editor-last3 = Heinzelmann |editor-first3 = Ursula |editor-last4 = Mason |editor-first4 = Laura |editor-last5 = Quinzio |editor-first5 = Geraldine |editor-last6 = Rath |editor-first6 = Eric |last-author-amp = yes }}</ref> The earliest known recipe for the modern variant was printed in ''Miss Parloa's Kitchen Companion'' in 1887 as \"chocolate cream pie\".<ref name=Goldstein />\n\nBoston cream pie is the official dessert of [[Massachusetts]], declared as such on December 12, 1996.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.sec.state.ma.us/cis/cismaf/mf1a.htm |title = Massachusetts Facts |publisher = Citizen Information Service, Massachusetts Secretary of the Commonwealth |access-date = March 30, 2015 |page = 6 }}</ref>\n\n==Variations==\nA [[Boston cream doughnut]] is a name for a [[Berliner (pastry)|Berliner]] filled with vanilla custard or ''cr\u00e8me p\u00e2tissi\u00e8re'' and topped with icing made from chocolate. This doughnut can be found at various restaurants including [[Dunkin']].\n\nThe [[Taiwan]] version of the Boston cream pie is a chiffon cake which does not include chocolate and resembles [[List of Chinese bakery products|Chinese baked goods]] more than the original Boston cream pie.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Food}}\n* [[Chocolate brownie]], another dessert created at an American hotel\n* [[List of pies, tarts and flans]]\n* [[List of regional dishes of the United States]]\n* [[Sachertorte]], the chocolate and apricot cake from a Viennese hotel that is associated with that city\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite web |url = http://whatscookingamerica.net/History/Cakes/BostonCreamPie.htm |title = Boston Cream Pie Recipe and History |last = Stradley |first = Linda |work = What's Cooking America |access-date = February 5, 2012 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last1 = Forbes |first1 = Esther |first2 = Arthur |last2 = Griffin |last-author-amp = yes |title = The Boston Book |url = https://archive.org/details/bostonbook00forb |publisher = Houghton Mifflin Company |year = 1947 }}\n* {{cite book |last1 = Morrisey |first1 = Louise Lane |first2 = Marion Lane |last2 = Sweeney |last-author-amp = yes |title = An Odd Volume of Cookery |ur