 29 November 2003)]\n*[http://www.washingtoncaps.com/history/History19791980.asp Washington Capitals History 1979-1980]{{Dead link|date=February 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061112174332/http://www.stlouisblues.com/history/alltime/transactions.html St. Louis Blues Team Records]\n*[http://static.espn.go.com/nhl/columns/expansion1/662095.html ''Foundation Begins with Goaltending'' by Al Morganti @ ESPN.com]\n*{{cite book |last=Greig |first=Murray |title=Big Bucks and Blue Pucks |year=1997 |publisher=Macmillan Canada |isbn= 978-0771574238|pages=213\u20137}}\n*{{cite book |last=Duplacey |first=James |title=Total Hockey: The official encyclopedia of the National Hockey League |year=1998 |publisher=Total Sports |isbn=0-8362-7114-9 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/totalhockeyoffic0000unse/page/498 498\u2013528] |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/totalhockeyoffic0000unse/page/498 }}\n\n{{NHL drafts}}\n{{1979\u201380 NHL season by team}}\n{{Edmonton Oilers}}\n{{Hartford Whalers}}\n{{Quebec Nordiques}}\n{{Winnipeg Jets (1972\u201396)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1979 Nhl Expansion Draft}}\n[[Category:1979\u201380 NHL season|Draft]]\n[[Category:History of the Edmonton Oilers|Expansion Draft]]\n[[Category:Hartford Whalers|Expansion Draft]]\n[[Category:Quebec Nordiques|Expansion Draft]]\n[[Category:History of the Winnipeg Jets|Expansion Draft]]\n[[Category:National Hockey League expansion drafts]]\n[[Category:Winnipeg Jets (1972\u201396)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox sports draft\n| name        = 1979 NHL Expansion Draft\n| image       = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| logo        = \n| logosize    = \n| date        = June 13, 1979\n| time        = \n| location    = \n| network     = \n| league      = \n| teams       = \n| first       = \n| most        = \n| fewest      = \n| first_round = \n| overall     = \n| prev        = [[1978 NHL Dispersal Draft|1978]]\n| next        = [[1991 NHL Expansion Draft|1991]]\n| expansion_teams  = [[Edmonton Oilers]]<br>[[Hartford Whalers]]<br>[[Quebec Nordiques]]<br>[[Winnipeg Jets (1972\u201396)|Winnipeg Jets]]\n}}\nThe '''1979 NHL Expansion Draft''' was held on June 13, 1979.  The draft took place to fill the rosters of the league's new teams for the [[1979\u201380 NHL season|1979\u201380 season]]: the [[Edmonton Oilers]], [[Hartford Whalers]], [[Quebec Nordiques]] and [[Winnipeg Jets (1972\u201396)|Winnipeg Jets]].  These four teams had joined the [[National Hockey League|NHL]] after a [[NHL\u2013WHA merger|merger agreement]] was reached with the [[World Hockey Association]].\n\nAs many WHA players also had their rights held by NHL teams, those NHL teams were allowed to reclaim their players.  In order to keep the NHL teams from plundering all the talent from the WHA-turned-NHL teams, each incoming franchise was allowed to protect up to two goaltenders and two skaters.  These were designated as \"priority selections\" in the Expansion Draft.\n\n==Rules==\n'''Reclaiming of players:''' The 17 existing NHL teams were allowed to reclaim any rights to former WHA players they held.  The four incoming franchises, however, were allowed to protect up to two goaltenders and two skaters, voiding their NHL rights.  These players were considered \"priority selections\" in the expansion draft.  Numerous deals were cut by the incoming teams to retain some of their players.  For instance, Quebec retained star forward [[R\u00e9al Cloutier|Real Cloutier]] by trading a first-round draft choice to the [[Chicago Blackhawks|Chicago Black Hawks]], which held Cloutier's rights; that pick was used to select perennial superstar [[Denis Savard]].\n\n[[Wayne Gretzky]] was a special case - although no team held his NHL rights, under existing rules he would have been removed from the Oilers and placed into the NHL Entry Draft.  However, Gretzky had been signed by Oilers owner [[Peter Pocklington]] to a personal services contract instead of a standard player contract.  Confronted with the probability of being drafted first overall by the last place Colorado Rockies, Gretzky refused to void his contract with Pocklington.  After deliberation, the Oilers were allowed to keep Gretzky as one of their priority selections, and agreed to choose last in each round of the [[1979 NHL Entry Draft]] as further compensation.\n\n[[Gordie Howe]] was a second special case - as a gentlemen's agreement between the [[Hartford Whalers]] and the [[Detroit Red Wings]], which held his NHL rights, the Red Wings declined to reclaim the 51-year-old Howe.\n\n[[Bobby Hull]] was a third special case - although he was formally reclaimed by the [[Chicago Blackhawks|Chicago Black Hawks]], the Black Hawks quickly released the 40-year-old Hull, allowing him to return to the [[Winnipeg Jets (1972-96)|Winnipeg Jets]].\n\n'''Expansion draft:''' Each of the 17 existing NHL teams were allowed to protect 15 skaters and two veteran goalies.\n\n'''Compensation:''' The 17 existing NHL teams received $125,000 for each player drafted, these payments being funded by the $6 million in franchise fees each of the former WHA teams paid to join the NHL.\n\n==WHA Dispersal Draft==\nFollowing the WHA season, and prior to the NHL reclaiming players, the WHA dispersed players from the teams not accepted into the NHL.  Players that were twenty years old or younger were available to all twenty-one NHL teams in the entry draft, the remaining players were made available (temporarily in the case of Liut) to the four merging teams from the WHA.<ref>Greig p.213</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1979/06/07/archives/nhl-players-group-consents-to-merger.html |title=N.H.L. Players\u2019 Group Consents to Merger |publisher=New York Times |access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>  Before their final season the WHA opted not to have an amateur draft and instead encouraged their teams to sign underage players.<ref>Greig p. 215</ref>  The Birmingham Bulls used seven players who were drafted in the [[1979 NHL Entry Draft]]: [[Rob Ramage]] (1st), [[Rick Vaive]] (5th), [[Craig Hartsburg]] (6th), [[Michel Goulet]] (20th), [[Gaston Gingras]] (27th), [[Pat Riggin]] (33rd), and [[Keith Crowder]] (57th).  Crowder began the season as a Bull but returned to the [[Peterborough Petes]] after just five games.  The Cincinnati Stingers used two who were drafted: [[Mike Gartner]] (4th) and [[Mark Messier]] (48th).  Messier was not old enough for the 1979 draft but was eligible because of his WHA service time.<ref>{{cite web |title=1979 Draft Quick Facts |url=http://www.hockeydraftcentral.com/1979/79facts.html |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>  The Winnipeg Jets used [[John Gibson (ice hockey, born 1959)|John Gibson]] (71st), but only on a ten tryout contract in March 1979 but was returned to the [[Niagara Falls Flyers]] before the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web |title=1979 NHL Draft Pick John Gibson |url=http://www.hockeydraftcentral.com/1979/79071.html |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"3\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"wikitable sortable sortable\" style=\"width:80%\"\n|-\n!!width=15% style=\"background:#F87A36;\"|Player\n!!width=4% style=\"background:#F87A36;\"|Drafted From\n!!width=6% style=\"background:#F87A36;\"|Drafted To\n|-\n|  [[Bryon Baltimore]] ([[defenceman (ice hockey)|D]]) || rowspan=\"7\" | [[Cincinnati Stingers]] || rowspan=\"9\" | [[Edmonton Oilers]]\n|-\n|  [[Kelly Davis]] (D) \n|-\n|  [[Dave Forbes]] ([[winger (ice hockey)|LW]]) \n|-\n|  [[Mike Liut]] ([[Goaltender|G]]) \n|-\n|  [[Michel Parizeau]] ([[centre (ice hockey)|C]]) \n|-\n|  [[Reg Thomas (ice hockey)|Reg Thomas]] (LW)\n|-\n|  [[Bryan Watson (ice hockey)|Bryan Watson]] (D) \n|-\n|  [[Dave Fortier]] (D) || rowspan=\"2\" | [[Indianapolis Racers]] \n|-\n|  [[Bruce Greig]] (LW) \n|-\n|  [[Steve Alley]] (LW) || rowspan=\"4\" | [[Birmingham Bulls (WHA)|Birmingham Bulls]] || rowspan=\"6\" | [[Hartford Whalers]]\n|-\n|  [[Tony Cassolato]] ([[winger (ice hockey)|RW]]) \n|-\n|  [[Paul Henderson]] (LW) \n|-\n|  [[Bob Stephenson (ice hockey)|Bob Stephenson]] (C) \n|-\n|  [[Byron Shutt]] (LW) || Cincinnati Stingers\n|-\n|  [[Al McLeod]] (D) || Indianapolis Racers\n|-\n|  [[Peter Marrin]] (C) || rowspan=\"3\" | Birmingham Bulls || rowspan=\"9\" | [[Quebec Nordiques]]\n|-\n|  [[John Stewart (ice hockey, born 1950)|John Stewart]] (C) \n|-\n|  [[Greg Tebbutt]] (D) \n|-\n|  [[Michel Dion]] (G) || rowspan=\"10\" | Cincinnati Stingers\n|-\n|  [[Dave Dornseif]] (D) \n|-\n|  [[Robbie Ftorek]] (C)\n|-\n|  [[Bill Gilligan]] (C) \n|-\n|  [[Barry Melrose]] (D)  \n|-\n|  [[Paul Stewart (ice hockey)|Paul Stewart]] (LW) \n|-\n|  [[Jamie Hislop]] (RW) || rowspan=\"4\" | [[Winnipeg Jets (1972\u201396)|Winnipeg Jets]]\n|-\n|  [[Barry Legge]] (D) \n|-\n|  [[Peter Marsh (ice hockey)|Peter Marsh]] (LW)  \n|-\n|  [[Craig Norwich]] (D) \n|}\n\n==Reclaimed players==\n''These are players whose NHL rights were reclaimed when the WHA merged with the NHL.<ref name=bluepucks/>''\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"3\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"wikitable sortable sortable\" style=\"width:80%\"\n|-\n\n!style=\"background:#F87A36;\" width=5%|NO.\n!!width=15% style=\"background:#F87A36;\"|Player\n!!width=4% style=\"background:#F87A36;\"|Reclaimed from\n!!width=6% style=\"background:#F87A36;\"|Reclaimed by\n|-\n| 1. || [[Kent Nilsson]] (LW) || rowspan=\"3\" | [[Winnipeg Jets (1972\u201396)|Winnipeg Jets]] || [[Atlanta Flames]]\n|-\n| 2. || [[Bobby Hull]] ([[winger (ice hockey)|LW]]) || rowspan=\"2\" |[[Chicago Blackhawks|Chicago Black Hawks]]\n|-\n| 3. || [[Terry Ruskowski]] (RW) \n|-\n| 4. || [[Doug Berry (ice hockey)|Doug Berry]] ([[centre (ice hockey)|C]]) || rowspan=\"2\" | [[Edmonton Oilers]] || [[Colorado Rockies (NHL)|Colorado Rockies]]\n|-\n| 5. || [[Wes George]] (LW) || rowspan=\"4\" |[[Detroit Red Wings]]\n|-\n| 6. || [[Glenn Hicks]] (LW) || rowspan=\"2\" | Winnipeg Jets\n|-\n| 7. || [[Barry Long (ice hockey)|Barry Long]] (D) \n|-\n| 8. || [[George Lyle 